{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3d5582e6-86ab-4456-82a0-cba36d27121e","content":"## Connecting MCP Inspector to a C# stdio Server\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a built DLL:\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourServer.dll`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector will spawn your server process, communicate over stdin/stdout, and display available tools, resources, and prompts.\n\n**4. Debug your tools:**\n- Browse the **Tools** tab to see discovered tools and their schemas.\n- Click a tool, fill in parameters, and hit **Run** to invoke it.\n- Inspect the request/response JSON in real time.\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** only. Any logging must go to **stderr** — stray stdout output will break the protocol.\n- If you use `Console.WriteLine` for logging, switch to `Console.Error.WriteLine`.\n- You can set environment variables in the Inspector UI if your server needs them.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aa41d5fd-4696-4cee-9153-223de5acbdfb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about MCP (Model Context Protocol) tooling. I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"F04D:1136F1:120CD49:146A016:69F94124"},"id":"2cb11691-be42-43ad-8a88-64ae80992546","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:00:32.013Z","parentId":"511400b9-ec03-40cb-aee8-124e0cd8bdb0"}
